  "insights": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Traditional use declined, led by withdrawal",
        "body": "Traditional contraceptive use among all women fell from 9.8 percent in 2022 to 8.1 percent in 2025. Withdrawal accounts for most traditional use and much of the decline, falling from 8.1 to 6.8 percent. Calendar or rhythm use also declined, from 1.7 to 1.3 percent. The traditional-use story is therefore mainly a withdrawal story."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Traditional use has its own regional geography",
        "body": "Eastern Visayas had the highest traditional method use at 12.1 percent, followed by Ilocos Region at 11.8 percent and Western Visayas at 10.8 percent. BARMM was lowest at 3.2 percent, with Cagayan Valley, Central Visayas, and NIR also on the lower end. This is not the same geography as modern use, where Davao Region, MIMAROPA, SOCCSKSARGEN, and Caraga stand out."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Withdrawal dominates the traditional method mix",
        "body": "Withdrawal was 6.8 percent nationally in 2025, compared with 1.3 percent for calendar or rhythm. In the highest-traditional regions, withdrawal is also the main method: Eastern Visayas was at 10.9 percent, Ilocos Region at 10.8 percent, and Central Luzon at 8.8 percent. Calendar or rhythm is most visible in Western Visayas at 3.1 percent, but even there it remains smaller than withdrawal."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Traditional use is concentrated in the middle reproductive ages",
        "body": "Traditional method use is highest at ages 35-39 and 40-44, both at 12.7 percent. It is much lower among women aged 15-19, at 0.6 percent, and lower again at ages 45-49. The age pattern does not simply rise across the reproductive span; it clusters in the middle years."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional and education differences are sharper than wealth differences",
        "body": "Traditional use ranges from 7.0 percent in the lowest wealth quintile to 9.2 percent in the middle quintile. That spread is smaller than the regional gap from 12.1 percent in Eastern Visayas to 3.2 percent in BARMM. Education also separates more sharply, from 13.9 percent among women with post-secondary education to 3.4 percent among women with Grades 11-12."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "Traditional method use among all women declined from 9.8 percent in 2022 to 8.1 percent in 2025.",
      "Withdrawal accounts for most traditional use nationally and in high-traditional regions.",
      "Traditional use has a distinct regional pattern, led by Eastern Visayas, Ilocos Region, and Western Visayas."
    ]
  }
